She reports having gastroenteritis with vomiting and diarrhoea since Monday. She requests a medical certificate to cover her absence from work for the past two days.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate professional response regarding the medical certificate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Provide a certificate covering Monday to Wednesday with examination date noted","Issue a certificate starting from Wednesday only","Decline to provide any certificate","Issue a certificate without specifying examination date","Provide a certificate with diagnosis only"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate response is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eprovide a certificate covering Monday to Wednesday with examination date noted\u003C/strong\u003E. Medical practitioners can certify periods of illness before the consultation date if they believe the patient was unfit during that time, provided they clearly document the examination date and period of incapacity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIssue a certificate starting from Wednesday only\u003C/strong\u003E - This unnecessarily restricts the certificate when retrospective certification is permitted\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecline to provide any certificate\u003C/strong\u003E - There is no valid reason to decline if you believe the patient\u0027s account\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIssue a certificate without specifying examination date\u003C/strong\u003E - The examination date must be clearly stated on all medical certificates\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvide a certificate with diagnosis only\u003C/strong\u003E - A patient\u2019s confidentiality must be upheld; no diagnosis or illness details should be included in a medical certificate unless the patient has given their consent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe certificate should include the date of examination, period of incapacity, and degree of incapacity, while respecting patient confidentiality regarding specific diagnoses if requested.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Medical certificates can cover periods before the consultation date if the practitioner believes the patient was unfit during that time.","Medical certificates must clearly state both the examination date and the period of believed incapacity.","Patients have the right to request that specific diagnoses be excluded from medical certificates."],"references":["Medical Council of New South Wales. Medical certificates: what you should know [online]. [Cited 2020 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.mcnsw.org.au/medical-certificates-what-you-should-know.","Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64882"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18827"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64882"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T09:48:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T09:49:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11560"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79578"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"18","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/18"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddd1\u200d\u2696\ufe0f","name":"Medicolegal","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group